The paper deals with the computational complexity of computing treewidth, a fundamental graph parameter that has applications in various areas of computer science such as algorithm design, database theory, and computational biology. The paper presents a lower bound on the sparsification of treewidth instances, which has implications for structural parameterizations of treewidth. This suggests that the paper is likely to be relevant to several subfields of computer science, including data structures (cs.DS), computational complexity (cs.CC), computational geometry (cs.CG), graph theory (cs.GT), and discrete mathematics (cs.DM).
